      "symbolism": "The Tablets represent the direct communication between God and humanity, the foundation of divine law, and the covenant relationship between God and Israel. The stone material symbolizes permanence and immutability of God's law. The breaking of the first tablets demonstrates that even the most sacred objects are secondary to moral behavior - when Israel sinned with the golden calf, the tablets themselves were destroyed. The preservation of both broken and whole tablets in the Ark teaches that even broken spiritual vessels retain holiness and should be honored.",
      "culturalSignificance": "The Tablets are the supreme symbol of Jewish law and ethics. They appear atop Torah scrolls in synagogues worldwide, are depicted in Jewish art and architecture, and represent Judaism in interfaith contexts. The tradition of keeping both broken and whole tablets has inspired countless teachings about honoring those who are 'broken' or fallen, and about the possibility of renewal. The Ten Commandments themselves form the ethical foundation not only of Judaism but of Western civilization."
